'''Anton Roux''' (born 5 June 1981) is a former [[South Africa]]n [[cricket]]er who is the current coach of the [[Netherlands national cricket team]]. Roux was born in [[New York City]] to South African parents.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/269/269811/269811.html Anton Roux player profile] <U+2013> CricketArchive. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> He moved back to South Africa aged five, playing both underage representative cricket and [[Association football|football]], and later attended [[Pretoria Boys High School]].<ref name="ce">[http://www.cricketeurope4.net/DATABASE/ARTICLES7/articles/000035/003529.shtml "Interview with Anton Roux"] <U+2013> CricketEurope. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> At South African domestic level, Roux played for [[Northerns cricket team|Northerns]] (previously Northern Transvaal), a second-tier team providing players to the top-level [[Titans cricket team|Titans]] franchise. An [[off-spin]]ner and competent lower-order [[batsman]], he made his {{Cric FC}} debut during the 2007<U+2013>08 season of the [[CSA Provincial Competitions|Provincial Three-Day Challenge]], playing two matches.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/269/269811/First-Class_Matches.html First-class matches played by Anton Roux (4)] <U+2013> CricketArchive. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> In his second match, against [[Namibia national cricket team|Namibia]], he took 3/30 in Namibia's second innings, his best figures at first-class level.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/124/124066.html Northerns v Namibia], South African Airways Provincial Three-Day Challenge 2007/08 (Pool B) <U+2013> CricketArchive. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> Roux also played four [[List A cricket|limited-overs]] matches in that season's Provincial One-Day Challenge, including the competition's final, in which Northerns lost to [[Gauteng cricket team|Gauteng]].<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/269/269811/ListA_Matches.html List A matches played by Anton Roux (4)] <U+2013> CricketArchive. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> He retired at the end of the following season to concentrate on his coaching career, having played two further first-class games.<ref name="ce"/>

For the 2005 and 2006 Dutch seasons, Roux served as [[playing coach]] of the [[Amstelveen]]-based Amsterdamsche Cricket Club (ACC), which plays in the top-level [[Topklasse (cricket)|Topklasse]] competition. During his playing career in South Africa, he held a coaching position with the [[University of Pretoria]]'s academy, and he later served as head coach of the Northerns Cricket Academy, following his retirement from playing.<ref name="ce"/> In July 2011, Roux was appointed head coach of the [[Pietermaritzburg]]-based [[KwaZulu-Natal Inland cricket team|KwaZulu-Natal Inland]] team for the 2011<U+2013>12 season, which plays in both the one-day and three-day provincial competitions.<ref>Jonathan Cook (21 July 2011). [http://www.witness.co.za/index.php?showcontent&global%5B_id%5D=65000 "Inland cricket: new coach for senior team"] <U+2013><U+00A0>''The Witness''. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> At the end of the season, he returned to the Netherlands to again coach ACC, and was replaced in the KZN Inland role by [[Grant Morgan (cricketer)|Grant Morgan]].<ref>(3 August 2012). [http://www.witness.co.za/index.php?showcontent&global%5B_id%5D=85539 "Ex-Titans star appointed KZN Inland Union head coach"] <U+2013> ''The Witness''. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> Roux had been involved in coaching the Dutch national side since 2011,<ref>Jonathan Cook (29 September 2011). [http://witsa.blueboxonline.com/index.php?showcontent&global%5B_id%5D=69275 "New coach arrives with fresh ideas for underperforming Inland"] <U+2013> ''The Witness''. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> and was later made a full-time assistant coach and statistical analyst.<ref>[[Peter Drinnen]] (2012). "The Netherlands National Cricket Team: How stats play their part in what we do". In [http://kncb.nl/wp-content/uploads/2012-Kleefstra-Almanak-zonder-AA.pdf "KLEEFSTRA ALMANAK 2012"] (p. 5) <U+2013> [[Koninklijke Nederlandse Cricket Bond]] (KNCB). Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> After [[Peter Drinnen]] left the position in October 2013, Roux took over as senior coach of the Netherlands, on an acting basis.<ref>(22 October 2013). [http://www.espncricinfo.com/netherlands/content/story/681333.html "Drinnen leaves Netherlands post"] <U+2013> ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref> He has since coached the team at the [[2013 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier|2013 World Twenty20 Qualifier]], [[2014 Cricket World Cup Qualifier|2014 World Cup Qualifier]], and the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20|2014 World Twenty20]].<ref>Alan Gardner (30 March 2014). [http://www.espncricinfo.com/world-t20/content/story/732727.html "Troubled Netherlands buoyed by World T20 showing"] <U+2013> ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 20 May 2014.</ref>

